WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.900
specific requests from a security perspective,

00:02.900 --> 00:04.420
because it's better equipped,

00:04.420 --> 00:08.140
it's more intelligence to be able to handle that.

00:08.140 --> 00:10.140
And that's what we call a proxy.

00:23.140 --> 00:26.140
One of the ways that we can provide really good security

00:26.140 --> 00:28.620
across a network is to use the concept

00:28.620 --> 00:30.320
of what we call a proxy.

00:43.200 --> 00:46.200
One of the ways that we can provide really good security

00:46.200 --> 00:48.680
across a network is to use the concept

00:48.680 --> 00:50.440
of what we call a proxy.

00:50.440 --> 00:51.720
Now, if you look at that word,

00:51.720 --> 00:53.960
if you look it up in a dictionary, for example,

00:53.960 --> 00:57.760
it'll say acting on behalf of something else.

00:57.760 --> 01:00.720
The idea is, as a request comes in,

01:00.720 --> 01:03.400
we redirect it to something else

01:03.400 --> 01:05.720
that is better equipped to make that decision.

01:05.720 --> 01:09.040
In other words, we build something specifically

01:09.040 --> 01:13.040
to handle specific requests from a security perspective

01:13.040 --> 01:14.560
because it's better equipped,

01:14.560 --> 01:18.280
it's more intelligence to be able to handle that.

01:18.280 --> 01:20.320
And that's what we call a proxy.

01:20.320 --> 01:23.360
A proxy typically is an application,

01:23.360 --> 01:25.400
and because it is an application,

01:25.400 --> 01:27.120
it's running at layer seven,

01:27.240 --> 01:30.080
and therefore has a lot of intelligence

01:30.080 --> 01:32.840
to be able to make decisions that we need

01:32.840 --> 01:36.720
in order to either allow or deny certain things.

01:36.720 --> 01:40.720
So the concept of a proxy server is exactly what you see here.

01:40.720 --> 01:44.200
It can typically be a server that's running applications

01:44.200 --> 01:48.600
that has intelligence to be able to make very informed

01:48.600 --> 01:51.640
decisions about almost anything.

01:51.640 --> 01:53.520
Perfect example of this would be

01:53.720 --> 01:56.680
an application proxy firewall,

01:56.680 --> 02:00.920
which is really an application that we've built

02:00.920 --> 02:03.320
to make very informed decisions,

02:03.320 --> 02:07.200
such as deep packet inspection, web content filtering,

02:07.200 --> 02:11.160
or anything else that you wanna be able to do at layer seven.

02:11.160 --> 02:14.040
And because we're doing it at layer seven,

02:14.040 --> 02:16.800
that's where we have the most intelligence

02:16.800 --> 02:20.040
to be able to make the best security decision.

02:20.040 --> 02:23.760
And here is what it looks like from a diagram perspective.

02:23.760 --> 02:27.040
You've got a client that's trying to make a connection

02:27.040 --> 02:30.920
to a server, but that is gonna be done through something

02:30.920 --> 02:33.520
in the middle called the proxy server,

02:33.520 --> 02:36.480
which is really an application that's better equipped

02:36.480 --> 02:41.480
to make that decision on behalf of all of the security rules

02:41.800 --> 02:44.240
that we need to be able to enforce.

02:44.240 --> 02:47.680
A different way to look at this is what you see here.

02:47.760 --> 02:52.120
So while the perceived connection is really from client

02:52.120 --> 02:56.160
to server, the connection is either allowed to happen

02:56.160 --> 02:58.200
or not through the proxy.

02:58.200 --> 03:01.880
So what we do is we redirect that decision

03:01.880 --> 03:04.320
or that request to the proxy.

03:04.320 --> 03:07.520
And because the proxy has been built specifically

03:07.520 --> 03:11.280
to make that decision, it will enforce certain rules

03:11.280 --> 03:16.080
and either allow or deny that connection to be established.

03:16.080 --> 03:19.480
So from a user's perspective at the client,

03:19.480 --> 03:22.840
that connection is happening from client to server,

03:22.840 --> 03:26.840
but it's really happening through the proxy server itself,

03:26.840 --> 03:29.040
which is again built specifically

03:29.040 --> 03:31.560
to handle those security decisions.

03:31.560 --> 03:33.520
And because it's an application,

03:33.520 --> 03:38.680
it can make some really informed decisions at that level.

03:38.680 --> 03:42.160
And so some of the things that we can do at layer seven

03:42.160 --> 03:44.080
are things like that.

03:44.080 --> 03:47.320
And that ends up being an application

03:47.320 --> 03:52.320
that actually changes IP addresses to other IP addresses.

03:53.840 --> 03:56.520
And if you think about how a company

03:56.520 --> 04:00.120
has an internal network that you might be part of,

04:00.120 --> 04:02.320
as you go out to the internet,

04:03.320 --> 04:06.360
we might want to change your IP address

04:06.360 --> 04:09.240
so that you can go out to the internet

04:09.240 --> 04:12.680
and be routable and be able to access things.

04:12.680 --> 04:16.120
But from a security perspective, what Nat can do

04:16.120 --> 04:18.880
is it can change the IP address

04:18.880 --> 04:22.720
and all of those things that look internal to the organization

04:22.720 --> 04:25.080
so that when you go out to the internet,

04:25.080 --> 04:28.560
anything that relates to the internal network

04:28.560 --> 04:32.640
and its IP addressing schemes can be hidden

04:32.640 --> 04:35.240
from anybody out there out on the internet.

04:35.240 --> 04:40.240
So Nat can be useful in hiding our real addressing schemes

04:40.280 --> 04:44.120
and if you remember to what all attacks require

04:44.120 --> 04:46.440
and that is the reconnaissance phase,

04:46.440 --> 04:49.600
you want to be able to hide a lot of what we have internally

04:49.600 --> 04:52.800
so that they're not visible to anyone out on the internet.

04:52.800 --> 04:57.080
So Nat can be really useful from a security perspective

04:57.080 --> 05:02.080
because it can be used to hide your real addressing schemes

05:02.080 --> 05:07.080
as you allow people to go out to the internet.

05:07.160 --> 05:11.120
Now something that's part of Nat is what we call Pat.

05:11.120 --> 05:13.760
So Nat is network address translation

05:13.760 --> 05:16.760
which translates internal IP addresses

05:16.760 --> 05:20.080
to routable IP addresses out on the internet

05:20.080 --> 05:22.880
but what might be needed as part of that

05:22.880 --> 05:26.080
is what we call Pat, port address translation

05:26.080 --> 05:28.120
and here's how this works.

05:28.120 --> 05:30.080
You might have a whole bunch of machines

05:30.080 --> 05:33.520
on the internal network that are going out to the internet.

05:33.520 --> 05:37.160
They could all use the same IP address

05:37.160 --> 05:39.960
that they've been changed to so that they can be routable

05:39.960 --> 05:41.800
across the outside internet.

05:41.800 --> 05:45.360
So a whole bunch of machines can go out with the same IP address

05:45.360 --> 05:47.880
but what would distinguish each one of them

05:47.880 --> 05:50.200
is the port numbers that are gonna be different

05:50.200 --> 05:52.440
for each one of those machines.

05:52.440 --> 05:55.480
And obviously what we have to do is we have to keep track

05:55.480 --> 05:58.600
of that so that when the request comes back

05:58.600 --> 06:00.720
we can route it back to the machine

06:00.720 --> 06:02.720
that originated this.

06:02.720 --> 06:06.480
That's what Nat provides and it is part of TCP IP.

06:06.480 --> 06:08.480
So here's a perfect example.

06:08.480 --> 06:11.960
Let's say that you are the machine

06:11.960 --> 06:15.680
that is making a request out to the internet.

06:15.680 --> 06:20.760
The Nat capable device or proxy that sits at your parameters

06:20.800 --> 06:25.440
would understand your source IP address, destination IP address,

06:25.440 --> 06:29.280
source port and destination port and change that

06:29.280 --> 06:31.640
to something that is routable.

06:31.640 --> 06:33.920
But it would have to keep track of that

06:33.920 --> 06:36.120
so that when the request comes back

06:36.120 --> 06:38.440
we can change it back and route it back

06:38.440 --> 06:40.480
to your specific machine.

06:40.480 --> 06:43.600
This is what Nat and Pat can do.

06:43.600 --> 06:45.560
And of course from a security perspective

06:45.560 --> 06:48.640
what you need to remember is that it can be useful

06:48.640 --> 06:51.720
in hiding our real addressing schemes

06:51.720 --> 06:54.920
as we allow machines from the inside of the network

06:54.920 --> 06:58.880
to actually go out to the internet and web.

06:58.880 --> 07:03.200
Now one of the other reasons why we need Nat and Pat

07:03.200 --> 07:07.800
is that we have what are called private address ranges

07:07.800 --> 07:11.400
that are used by organizations internally.

07:11.400 --> 07:13.800
And so if you're a large organization

07:13.800 --> 07:16.320
you might be in the range of the 10 dot

07:16.320 --> 07:18.200
that is outlined here.

07:18.200 --> 07:19.880
As you go out to the internet

07:19.880 --> 07:22.920
those IP addresses are not routable.

07:22.920 --> 07:25.600
So it is Nat that needs to change it

07:25.600 --> 07:27.800
to something that is routable.

07:27.800 --> 07:31.680
And then when it comes back we routed back to your machine.

07:31.680 --> 07:35.040
It's Nat and Pat that does that.

07:35.040 --> 07:37.320
Now as far as the exam is concerned

07:37.320 --> 07:42.320
you don't need to memorize the private IP address ranges

07:42.320 --> 07:46.920
that are specified for example in RFC 1918

07:46.920 --> 07:49.240
which talks about private addresses

07:49.240 --> 07:52.040
that can be used by companies.

07:52.120 --> 07:55.480
But these are the ones that are allocated

07:55.480 --> 07:58.360
as being private and of course not routable

07:58.360 --> 07:59.640
across the internet.

07:59.640 --> 08:02.560
And that's why we need Nat and Pat

08:02.560 --> 08:06.000
to be able to handle this nicely for us.

